And the main thing
here was the risk.

00:12:08.760 --> 00:12:11.970 align:middle line:84%
In particular, in
village India, we

00:12:11.970 --> 00:12:15.090 align:middle line:84%
looked at the risk
of harvest yields

00:12:15.090 --> 00:12:22.560 align:middle line:84%
on various crops, of crops by
soil type, of income by type.

00:12:22.560 --> 00:12:26.310 align:middle line:84%
And we uniformly
saw a very high risk

00:12:26.310 --> 00:12:31.260 align:middle line:84%
on all these categories, as
well as some diversification

00:12:31.260 --> 00:12:32.180 align:middle line:90%
possibilities.

00:12:32.180 --> 00:12:37.680 align:middle line:84%
So for income, not everyone
has the same income sources,

00:12:37.680 --> 00:12:39.420 align:middle line:90%
and there's high risk of each.

00:12:39.420 --> 00:12:43.750 align:middle line:84%
But the covariances are
sometimes relatively low.

00:12:43.750 --> 00:12:46.560 align:middle line:84%
So the focus here
was on the fact

00:12:46.560 --> 00:12:49.020 align:middle line:84%
that households are not
completely diversified.

00:12:49.020 --> 00:12:51.780 align:middle line:84%
If all the households
did the same thing

00:12:51.780 --> 00:12:54.720 align:middle line:84%
if, they planted the same
crops in the same soil,

00:12:54.720 --> 00:12:57.780 align:middle line:84%
and have the same
income sources then

00:12:57.780 --> 00:13:03.070 align:middle line:84%
their initial outcomes would
be essentially the same.

00:13:03.070 --> 00:13:06.630 align:middle line:84%
And if that's true, then
there's not much left to share.

00:13:06.630 --> 00:13:08.110 align:middle line:90%
But we see the opposite.

00:13:08.110 --> 00:13:11.970 align:middle line:84%
We see they're not diversified
over all these various crops,

00:13:11.970 --> 00:13:13.600 align:middle line:90%
and soils, and activities.

00:13:13.600 --> 00:13:16.350 align:middle line:84%
So there's a lot of
idiosyncratic risk.

00:13:16.350 --> 00:13:19.230 align:middle line:84%
And that was what was clear
from this picture of what

00:13:19.230 --> 00:13:22.890 align:middle line:84%
we call the Rocky Mountains,
where the ups and downs are not

00:13:22.890 --> 00:13:26.640 align:middle line:84%
together, not going up together
across households in a given

00:13:26.640 --> 00:13:28.540 align:middle line:90%
year, and so on.

00:13:28.540 --> 00:13:31.500 align:middle line:84%
Whereas, they do achieve
a lot of smoothing.

00:13:31.500 --> 00:13:34.890 align:middle line:84%
So something is
happening in the villages

00:13:34.890 --> 00:13:40.170 align:middle line:84%
that whatever mechanism it is,
is allowing them to smooth.

00:13:40.170 --> 00:13:46.020 align:middle line:84%
Now one question that's come up
in Piazza are these profiles.

00:13:46.020 --> 00:13:49.470 align:middle line:84%
I mean so this is
a bit of a review,

00:13:49.470 --> 00:13:50.700 align:middle line:90%
but kind of interesting.

00:13:50.700 --> 00:13:55.110 align:middle line:84%
We see this income
profile from low to high.

00:13:55.110 --> 00:13:57.480 align:middle line:84%
Households with a lot
of land are consistently

00:13:57.480 --> 00:14:00.300 align:middle line:84%
getting higher income,
despite the fluctuations.

00:14:00.300 --> 00:14:04.450 align:middle line:84%
And there's a big
compression here.

00:14:04.450 --> 00:14:06.630 align:middle line:84%
So something is
transferring income

00:14:06.630 --> 00:14:10.170 align:middle line:84%
from the landed households
to the landless.

00:14:10.170 --> 00:14:13.110 align:middle line:84%
But a little bit of this
profile does remain.

00:14:13.110 --> 00:14:14.707 align:middle line:90%
So it's not equal treatment.

00:14:14.707 --> 00:14:16.290 align:middle line:84%
It's not as though
everyone is getting

00:14:16.290 --> 00:14:18.390 align:middle line:90%
the same amount of everything.

00:14:18.390 --> 00:14:21.510 align:middle line:84%
There is heterogeneity
in the treatment.

00:14:21.510 --> 00:14:24.510 align:middle line:84%
What that mechanism
is, is not so clear.

00:14:24.510 --> 00:14:27.690 align:middle line:84%
It's some kind of, at
least over these 10 years,

00:14:27.690 --> 00:14:32.500 align:middle line:84%
redistribution of income
from the wealthy to the poor.

00:14:32.500 --> 00:14:34.810 align:middle line:90%
But it doesn't work perfectly.

00:14:34.810 --> 00:14:37.790 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't completely
equalize things.

00:14:37.790 --> 00:14:40.210 align:middle line:84%
So this lecture was
featuring something

00:14:40.210 --> 00:14:42.460 align:middle line:84%
we had done in the
previous one, which

00:14:42.460 --> 00:14:45.970 align:middle line:84%
is to determine the pareto
optimal allocation of risk,

00:14:45.970 --> 00:14:50.350 align:middle line:84%
we maximize lambda weighted
sums of expected utilities,

00:14:50.350 --> 00:14:53.360 align:middle line:84%
subject to the
resource constraint.

00:14:53.360 --> 00:14:58.330 align:middle line:84%
And this way of
dealing with problems

00:14:58.330 --> 00:15:03.170 align:middle line:84%
generalizes considerably and
in the subsequent lectures.

00:15:03.170 --> 00:15:04.810 align:middle line:84%
So when we solved
this problem, we

00:15:04.810 --> 00:15:07.000 align:middle line:84%
looked at the first
order conditions.

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:10.090 align:middle line:84%
We could see that weighted
marginal utilities should

00:15:10.090 --> 00:15:14.530 align:middle line:84%
be equalized to a common
Lagrange multiplier.

00:15:14.530 --> 00:15:16.360 align:middle line:84%
And you can do the
algebra, and actually

00:15:16.360 --> 00:15:20.590 align:middle line:84%
solve for the consumption
that's supposed to result,

00:15:20.590 --> 00:15:24.070 align:middle line:84%
and get these kinds of
closed form solutions

00:15:24.070 --> 00:15:29.110 align:middle line:84%
having to do with consumption
moving with the aggregate,

00:15:29.110 --> 00:15:34.420 align:middle line:84%
and not moving at all
with idiosyncratic shocks,

00:15:34.420 --> 00:15:37.605 align:middle line:90%
if the risk sharing is optimal.

00:15:37.605 --> 00:15:38.980 align:middle line:84%
So here is another
version of it,

00:15:38.980 --> 00:15:42.850 align:middle line:84%
individual consumption co-moves
with aggregate consumption

00:15:42.850 --> 00:15:45.430 align:middle line:84%
for all the households,
but should not

00:15:45.430 --> 00:15:48.580 align:middle line:84%
move with things like
individual incomes

00:15:48.580 --> 00:15:50.840 align:middle line:84%
once we control
for the aggregate.

00:15:50.840 --> 00:15:57.040 align:middle line:84%
So we tested this model to see
whether these coefficients were

00:15:57.040 --> 00:16:00.040 align:middle line:90%
0 or not, and largely they are.

00:16:00.040 --> 00:16:02.980 align:middle line:84%
I mean there is some
residual risk that

00:16:02.980 --> 00:16:04.960 align:middle line:84%
is being borne by
the households,

00:16:04.960 --> 00:16:07.370 align:middle line:84%
depending on the village
and the source of income.

00:16:07.370 --> 00:16:10.253 align:middle line:84%
But the benchmark
was doing quite well.

00:16:10.253 --> 00:16:11.170 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:16:11.170 --> 00:16:12.550 align:middle line:84%
ROBERT TOWNSEND: I
would be delighted.

00:16:12.550 --> 00:16:13.360 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:16:13.360 --> 00:16:17.590 align:middle line:90%
I mean here, we assume--

00:16:17.590 --> 00:16:18.880 align:middle line:90%
I see the sample.

00:16:18.880 --> 00:16:23.320 align:middle line:84%
There was about 40
households in each villagers.

00:16:23.320 --> 00:16:26.890 align:middle line:84%
But in this model, we
assume that the households

00:16:26.890 --> 00:16:29.360 align:middle line:90%
should be large amount.

00:16:29.360 --> 00:16:33.520 align:middle line:84%
If not, then the
idiosyncratic risk

00:16:33.520 --> 00:16:36.340 align:middle line:90%
might not be shared, right?

00:16:36.340 --> 00:16:40.810 align:middle line:84%
And for example, if there was
just two households and two

00:16:40.810 --> 00:16:49.460 align:middle line:84%
situations, then although they
face the idiosyncratic risks,

00:16:49.460 --> 00:16:56.840 align:middle line:84%
but there was like 0.25
probability both of them

00:16:56.840 --> 00:17:01.670 align:middle line:84%
were facing negative
shocks and/or both of them

00:17:01.670 --> 00:17:03.030 align:middle line:90%
face the positive shock.

00:17:03.030 --> 00:17:05.160 align:middle line:90%
So they cannot share the risks.

00:17:05.160 --> 00:17:13.160 align:middle line:84%
So in this model, we assume
the sample is large enough.

00:17:13.160 --> 00:17:19.819 align:middle line:84%
That is why we think that the
idiosyncratic shocks will not

00:17:19.819 --> 00:17:22.910 align:middle line:90%
affect people's consumption?

00:17:22.910 --> 00:17:25.667 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, each household
consumption.

00:17:25.667 --> 00:17:26.500 align:middle line:90%
ROBERT TOWNSEND: OK.

00:17:26.500 --> 00:17:30.100 align:middle line:90%
So it's a great question.

00:17:30.100 --> 00:17:34.780 align:middle line:84%
What can we test if we only
have a subset of the households,

00:17:34.780 --> 00:17:38.060 align:middle line:90%
and are we being misled?

00:17:38.060 --> 00:17:41.150 align:middle line:84%
Well, actually you
could think about it

00:17:41.150 --> 00:17:44.030 align:middle line:90%
as testing for subsets.

00:17:44.030 --> 00:17:45.750 align:middle line:90%
And the theory holds.

00:17:45.750 --> 00:17:48.835 align:middle line:84%
Of course, what is aggregate
consumption for two

00:17:48.835 --> 00:17:50.960 align:middle line:84%
households would be different
from what it would be

00:17:50.960 --> 00:17:54.010 align:middle line:90%
if you had data on all of them.

00:17:54.010 --> 00:17:57.185 align:middle line:84%
But the theory still works
for two, or three, or just

00:17:57.185 --> 00:17:57.685 align:middle line:90%
a handful.

00:17:57.685 --> 00:18:00.370 align:middle line:90%


00:18:00.370 --> 00:18:02.500 align:middle line:84%
If they are bearing
risk optimally,

00:18:02.500 --> 00:18:05.815 align:middle line:84%
then they should be bearing
risk optimally in any subset.

00:18:05.815 --> 00:18:08.750 align:middle line:90%


00:18:08.750 --> 00:18:11.160 align:middle line:90%
Let me put that a different way.

00:18:11.160 --> 00:18:16.680 align:middle line:84%
The aggregate consumption within
the group may be moving around.

00:18:16.680 --> 00:18:20.360 align:middle line:84%
Individual consumptions in the
group should move with that.

00:18:20.360 --> 00:18:22.530 align:middle line:84%
The group consumption
actually could

00:18:22.530 --> 00:18:24.870 align:middle line:84%
look like an
idiosyncratic shock if we

00:18:24.870 --> 00:18:27.450 align:middle line:90%
considered the whole village.

00:18:27.450 --> 00:18:30.470 align:middle line:84%
So yet more
restrictions are implied

00:18:30.470 --> 00:18:35.520 align:middle line:84%
when we and if we had data
from the larger sample.

00:18:35.520 --> 00:18:38.890 align:middle line:84%
But you can still
test the theory

00:18:38.890 --> 00:18:41.440 align:middle line:84%
with a small number
of households.

00:18:41.440 --> 00:18:44.380 align:middle line:84%
It's just that it's
not as powerful.

00:18:44.380 --> 00:18:46.510 align:middle line:90%
You could reject, however.

00:18:46.510 --> 00:18:47.630 align:middle line:90%
Does that help?

00:18:47.630 --> 00:18:48.657 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:18:48.657 --> 00:18:49.490 align:middle line:90%
ROBERT TOWNSEND: OK.

00:18:49.490 --> 00:18:50.490 align:middle line:90%
It was a great question.

00:18:50.490 --> 00:18:54.760 align:middle line:90%


00:18:54.760 --> 00:18:58.870 align:middle line:84%
So then the next
thing we did was

00:18:58.870 --> 00:19:03.010 align:middle line:84%
to take the same theory to
different applications, back

00:19:03.010 --> 00:19:07.600 align:middle line:84%
to medieval villages, and the
landholding patterns which

00:19:07.600 --> 00:19:10.270 align:middle line:84%
are spread out all over
the different fields.

00:19:10.270 --> 00:19:13.000 align:middle line:84%
And the idea is, does
that make sense or not,

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:17.440 align:middle line:84%
and would dividing up the
land in that way exactly

00:19:17.440 --> 00:19:21.020 align:middle line:84%
achieve an optimal allocation
of risk bearing or not.

00:19:21.020 --> 00:19:24.250 align:middle line:84%
So we took the
different types of land

00:19:24.250 --> 00:19:27.310 align:middle line:84%
to have a different
vector of yields.

00:19:27.310 --> 00:19:30.970 align:middle line:84%
We talked about the
endowment, so to speak,

00:19:30.970 --> 00:19:36.370 align:middle line:84%
the yields of land type
k across states epsilon.

00:19:36.370 --> 00:19:40.420 align:middle line:84%
And then we have
capital K types of land

00:19:40.420 --> 00:19:43.660 align:middle line:90%
and capital S types of shocks.

00:19:43.660 --> 00:19:46.570 align:middle line:84%
We can look at the
covariance and the risk, just

00:19:46.570 --> 00:19:48.770 align:middle line:90%
the way we did in India.

00:19:48.770 --> 00:19:51.490 align:middle line:84%
So again, we get this
picture, very, very

00:19:51.490 --> 00:19:54.880 align:middle line:84%
risky with some
covariances pretty low.

00:19:54.880 --> 00:19:57.580 align:middle line:84%
And then I took you through
a series of examples

00:19:57.580 --> 00:20:01.660 align:middle line:84%
to see how close we could get
to an optimal allocation of risk

00:20:01.660 --> 00:20:02.530 align:middle line:90%
bearing.

00:20:02.530 --> 00:20:06.190 align:middle line:84%
The first was household
1 is all of land type 1.

00:20:06.190 --> 00:20:08.620 align:middle line:84%
Household 2 has
all of land type 2.

00:20:08.620 --> 00:20:11.590 align:middle line:84%
But these returns
do not co-move,

00:20:11.590 --> 00:20:16.150 align:middle line:84%
hence this would not constitute
an optimal allocation

00:20:16.150 --> 00:20:17.140 align:middle line:90%
of risk bearing.

00:20:17.140 --> 00:20:19.210 align:middle line:90%
Household 1 would go 10, 6.

00:20:19.210 --> 00:20:21.790 align:middle line:90%
Household 2 would go 2, 4.

00:20:21.790 --> 00:20:24.280 align:middle line:84%
So although the
aggregate is going down,

00:20:24.280 --> 00:20:29.980 align:middle line:84%
I should say, from 12 to 10,
household 2's consumption

00:20:29.980 --> 00:20:33.370 align:middle line:84%
if they ate all their own
crops would be going up.

00:20:33.370 --> 00:20:35.090 align:middle line:90%
So that's a restriction.

00:20:35.090 --> 00:20:37.810 align:middle line:84%
Then we considered a
different way of doing it.

00:20:37.810 --> 00:20:40.030 align:middle line:90%
Give those household shares.

00:20:40.030 --> 00:20:46.030 align:middle line:84%
Household j say
having a share alpha j

00:20:46.030 --> 00:20:48.200 align:middle line:90%
of the two different crops.

00:20:48.200 --> 00:20:53.200 align:middle line:84%
So now, this thing goes in
the aggregate 12, 10, 7.

00:20:53.200 --> 00:20:56.200 align:middle line:84%
Obviously whatever
household 1's share

00:20:56.200 --> 00:21:00.160 align:middle line:84%
is, if it's like one third,
it's 1/3 of that aggregate.

00:21:00.160 --> 00:21:03.640 align:middle line:84%
Household 2's shares would
be 2/3 of that aggregate.

00:21:03.640 --> 00:21:06.010 align:middle line:84%
So now they're each
bearing a constant share

00:21:06.010 --> 00:21:08.320 align:middle line:84%
of the aggregate and
their consumptions

00:21:08.320 --> 00:21:11.320 align:middle line:90%
are moving with the aggregate.

00:21:11.320 --> 00:21:14.000 align:middle line:90%
So that might actually work.

00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:14.900 align:middle line:90%
That's this.

00:21:14.900 --> 00:21:17.290 align:middle line:84%
And then we looked at
special utility functions,

00:21:17.290 --> 00:21:20.680 align:middle line:84%
and started fussing about
intercepts, and risk aversion,

00:21:20.680 --> 00:21:21.740 align:middle line:90%
and so on.

00:21:21.740 --> 00:21:23.980 align:middle line:84%
But then we come
to the general idea

00:21:23.980 --> 00:21:29.590 align:middle line:84%
that we have as many land types
with independent return vectors

00:21:29.590 --> 00:21:31.790 align:middle line:90%
as we have states of the world.

00:21:31.790 --> 00:21:35.960 align:middle line:84%
And then we have a target
optimal consumption allocation.

00:21:35.960 --> 00:21:39.010 align:middle line:84%
So we're trying to achieve
this allocation that

00:21:39.010 --> 00:21:42.790 align:middle line:84%
came from maximizing a lambda
weighted sums of utilities

00:21:42.790 --> 00:21:48.490 align:middle line:84%
by dividing the different
land types into shares.

00:21:48.490 --> 00:21:51.370 align:middle line:84%
Except now we have
even more power,

00:21:51.370 --> 00:21:54.580 align:middle line:84%
because we do not require
that household j have

00:21:54.580 --> 00:21:57.400 align:middle line:84%
the same shares and all
of the land types k.

00:21:57.400 --> 00:22:01.330 align:middle line:84%
We have this alpha jk for
household j in the land type k.

00:22:01.330 --> 00:22:03.010 align:middle line:90%
And it's not perfect.

00:22:03.010 --> 00:22:06.040 align:middle line:84%
But in general, since
this vector of endowments

00:22:06.040 --> 00:22:11.170 align:middle line:84%
is non-singular, you can
solve for the consumptions.

00:22:11.170 --> 00:22:15.380 align:middle line:84%
And one hopes that the shares
will be positive in the end.

00:22:15.380 --> 00:22:17.920 align:middle line:84%
So if there are as
many types of land

00:22:17.920 --> 00:22:20.290 align:middle line:84%
as there are states
of the world,

00:22:20.290 --> 00:22:24.490 align:middle line:84%
they have a shot at achieving
the optimum by entirely

00:22:24.490 --> 00:22:27.190 align:middle line:84%
dividing up the
land, and not having

00:22:27.190 --> 00:22:31.340 align:middle line:84%
to give gifts or transfers to
one another after the fact.

00:22:31.340 --> 00:22:34.040 align:middle line:90%
So then we come to--

00:22:34.040 --> 00:22:36.790 align:middle line:84%
we put in particular
utility functions,

00:22:36.790 --> 00:22:42.010 align:middle line:84%
and we assumed that
we're going to solve

00:22:42.010 --> 00:22:46.570 align:middle line:84%
this problem, maximizing lambda
weighted sums of utilities,

00:22:46.570 --> 00:22:49.330 align:middle line:90%
by the shares alpha jk.

00:22:49.330 --> 00:22:51.970 align:middle line:84%
But we're going to
assume that there

00:22:51.970 --> 00:22:56.120 align:middle line:84%
are fewer land types than
there are states of the world,

00:22:56.120 --> 00:23:01.720 align:middle line:84%
namely only two types
of land, and a larger

00:23:01.720 --> 00:23:04.190 align:middle line:90%
number as states of the world.

00:23:04.190 --> 00:23:08.950 align:middle line:84%
So now, we know we in general
cannot achieve an optimum.

00:23:08.950 --> 00:23:12.310 align:middle line:84%
But we were trying to describe
this constrained optimal

00:23:12.310 --> 00:23:13.510 align:middle line:90%
arrangement.

00:23:13.510 --> 00:23:17.050 align:middle line:84%
I guess what I want to emphasize
is despite the restrictions,

00:23:17.050 --> 00:23:19.180 align:middle line:84%
we're still solving this
programming problem.

00:23:19.180 --> 00:23:22.000 align:middle line:84%
We're maximizing
lambda weighted sums

00:23:22.000 --> 00:23:24.400 align:middle line:84%
of utilities subject
to constraints,

00:23:24.400 --> 00:23:26.410 align:middle line:84%
namely the shares
have to add up.

00:23:26.410 --> 00:23:29.320 align:middle line:84%
So the method of
achieving characterizing

00:23:29.320 --> 00:23:32.510 align:middle line:84%
pareto optimal
allocations is the same.

00:23:32.510 --> 00:23:35.860 align:middle line:84%
And then we looked to see
with those particular utility

00:23:35.860 --> 00:23:40.420 align:middle line:84%
functions how far off we would
be from achieving the optimum.

00:23:40.420 --> 00:23:43.270 align:middle line:84%
And here you can actually see,
as the aggregate endowment

00:23:43.270 --> 00:23:45.070 align:middle line:90%
moves the adjustment.

00:23:45.070 --> 00:23:47.890 align:middle line:84%
In other words, even if they
did as much as they could

00:23:47.890 --> 00:23:51.910 align:middle line:84%
by dividing up the two land
types, it would not be perfect.

00:23:51.910 --> 00:23:55.330 align:middle line:84%
And there should be incoming
or outgoing transfers

00:23:55.330 --> 00:23:59.410 align:middle line:84%
to try to make up the difference
to get to the full risk sharing

00:23:59.410 --> 00:24:00.670 align:middle line:90%
optimum.

00:24:00.670 --> 00:24:03.110 align:middle line:84%
And that was the
end of this lecture.

00:24:03.110 --> 00:24:05.200 align:middle line:84%
Are there questions
about what we did

00:24:05.200 --> 00:24:07.525 align:middle line:84%
or what we were trying to
accomplish in lecture 8?

00:24:07.525 --> 00:24:11.160 align:middle line:90%


00:24:11.160 --> 00:24:14.730 align:middle line:84%
So then the second of the
two application lectures

00:24:14.730 --> 00:24:17.850 align:middle line:84%
included production
in lecture 9.

00:24:17.850 --> 00:24:22.410 align:middle line:84%
And the main difference
between what we did just now

00:24:22.410 --> 00:24:25.740 align:middle line:84%
and this lecture, is we actually
have physical production,

00:24:25.740 --> 00:24:29.310 align:middle line:84%
rather than treating
output as an endowment.

00:24:29.310 --> 00:24:33.350 align:middle line:84%
But we still solve this
programming problem.

00:24:33.350 --> 00:24:36.580 align:middle line:84%
So we're maximizing
lambda weighted sums

00:24:36.580 --> 00:24:40.390 align:middle line:84%
of expected utilities,
just as before,

00:24:40.390 --> 00:24:44.950 align:middle line:84%
subject to resource
constraints, just as before.

00:24:44.950 --> 00:24:51.040 align:middle line:84%
The choice variables now include
the transfers, just as before,

00:24:51.040 --> 00:24:54.820 align:middle line:84%
but we also are
choosing which projects

00:24:54.820 --> 00:24:58.280 align:middle line:84%
to fund and by how much
capital investment.

00:24:58.280 --> 00:25:01.810 align:middle line:84%
So the reason that transfers
are the same as before,

00:25:01.810 --> 00:25:04.780 align:middle line:84%
is because we have
transfers or consumption.

00:25:04.780 --> 00:25:07.630 align:middle line:84%
You can move consumption
around by moving transfers.

00:25:07.630 --> 00:25:13.240 align:middle line:84%
So it's arbitrary choice
whether to solve for c or tau.

00:25:13.240 --> 00:25:15.010 align:middle line:84%
The more interesting
part, because it's

00:25:15.010 --> 00:25:17.860 align:middle line:84%
new to this lecture,
are these capital

00:25:17.860 --> 00:25:21.550 align:middle line:84%
stocks, which has to
do with deciding what

00:25:21.550 --> 00:25:25.510 align:middle line:84%
to do with the current wealth,
namely eat it or invested

00:25:25.510 --> 00:25:28.330 align:middle line:90%
in projects for tomorrow.

00:25:28.330 --> 00:25:31.720 align:middle line:84%
Here is the starting
point, w, which

00:25:31.720 --> 00:25:34.180 align:middle line:84%
is the trees and the
fruit from the trees.

00:25:34.180 --> 00:25:38.380 align:middle line:84%
And this was the ending point,
what to do, either eat or save.

00:25:38.380 --> 00:25:40.720 align:middle line:84%
Oh then, back to the
accounting identities,

00:25:40.720 --> 00:25:44.800 align:middle line:84%
you either eat something or
save something, as in the flows.

00:25:44.800 --> 00:25:48.380 align:middle line:84%
So we got two first order
conditions out of this problem,

00:25:48.380 --> 00:25:51.790 align:middle line:84%
one very familiar, lambda
weighted marginal utilities

00:25:51.790 --> 00:25:53.540 align:middle line:90%
are equated to each other.

00:25:53.540 --> 00:25:55.780 align:middle line:84%
We also got a new
equation having

00:25:55.780 --> 00:25:59.410 align:middle line:84%
to do with the marginal
utility of consumption today,

00:25:59.410 --> 00:26:03.170 align:middle line:84%
and the marginal utility
of consumption next period.

00:26:03.170 --> 00:26:06.590 align:middle line:84%
And those typically will
balance each other off

00:26:06.590 --> 00:26:08.510 align:middle line:90%
for any project they're running.

00:26:08.510 --> 00:26:11.840 align:middle line:84%
There was an issue that this
thing could have been negative,

00:26:11.840 --> 00:26:16.342 align:middle line:84%
in which case that project
would not be implemented,

00:26:16.342 --> 00:26:18.800 align:middle line:84%
because they would actually
not want to put stuff in there.

00:26:18.800 --> 00:26:20.060 align:middle line:90%
They'd want to take stuff out.

00:26:20.060 --> 00:26:21.680 align:middle line:90%
But they hit zero.

00:26:21.680 --> 00:26:25.940 align:middle line:84%
So the rest of it was
to take expressions

00:26:25.940 --> 00:26:27.440 align:middle line:84%
for these first
order conditions,

00:26:27.440 --> 00:26:29.630 align:middle line:90%
and start manipulating them.

00:26:29.630 --> 00:26:32.120 align:middle line:84%
I'm not going to
review that today.

00:26:32.120 --> 00:26:33.800 align:middle line:90%
It's algebra.

00:26:33.800 --> 00:26:35.700 align:middle line:90%
It's straightforward.

00:26:35.700 --> 00:26:37.970 align:middle line:84%
We can even make
some assumptions

00:26:37.970 --> 00:26:41.810 align:middle line:84%
about linear technologies,
subject to risk,

00:26:41.810 --> 00:26:45.050 align:middle line:90%
and quadratic utility functions.

00:26:45.050 --> 00:26:49.130 align:middle line:84%
And when we did that, we
got two expressions directly

00:26:49.130 --> 00:26:52.220 align:middle line:84%
from the theory that we
could take to the data.

00:26:52.220 --> 00:26:56.270 align:middle line:84%
One, we can measure
from the data

00:26:56.270 --> 00:27:00.920 align:middle line:84%
how household j returns
are moving with the village

00:27:00.920 --> 00:27:02.990 align:middle line:84%
aggregate return,
this beta being

00:27:02.990 --> 00:27:07.010 align:middle line:84%
a measure of the covariation
of household j's return

00:27:07.010 --> 00:27:08.720 align:middle line:90%
with the village average.

00:27:08.720 --> 00:27:14.480 align:middle line:84%
Then having used the panel
data to get these beta j's, we

00:27:14.480 --> 00:27:18.620 align:middle line:84%
look in the cross section to
see how the betas are related

00:27:18.620 --> 00:27:23.750 align:middle line:84%
to each other, and in particular
to the overall average

00:27:23.750 --> 00:27:25.530 align:middle line:90%
or expected return.

00:27:25.530 --> 00:27:28.070 align:middle line:84%
So the main empirical
finding here

00:27:28.070 --> 00:27:31.760 align:middle line:84%
was that returns
have to be higher

00:27:31.760 --> 00:27:33.920 align:middle line:84%
when the betas are
higher, because

00:27:33.920 --> 00:27:38.060 align:middle line:84%
those particular activities
from household j co-move

00:27:38.060 --> 00:27:39.830 align:middle line:90%
move a lot with the aggregate.

00:27:39.830 --> 00:27:45.170 align:middle line:84%
So in effect, it's very risky,
not so many diversification

00:27:45.170 --> 00:27:47.720 align:middle line:84%
possibilities come from
including household

00:27:47.720 --> 00:27:50.520 align:middle line:90%
j in the village portfolio.

00:27:50.520 --> 00:27:53.600 align:middle line:84%
And so if they're
going to be running

00:27:53.600 --> 00:27:56.360 align:middle line:84%
those projects of
household j, there

00:27:56.360 --> 00:27:58.490 align:middle line:84%
has to be a compensating
differential,

00:27:58.490 --> 00:28:01.200 align:middle line:84%
and that's the higher
expected return.

00:28:01.200 --> 00:28:06.035 align:middle line:84%
So then we started adopting this
language of risk premia, which

00:28:06.035 --> 00:28:09.230 align:middle line:84%
is the difference between
the expected return

00:28:09.230 --> 00:28:12.000 align:middle line:90%
and the risk-free rate.

00:28:12.000 --> 00:28:15.320 align:middle line:84%
The risk premia has to
compensate for the risk.

00:28:15.320 --> 00:28:17.510 align:middle line:84%
So then we went
to the Thai data,

00:28:17.510 --> 00:28:19.110 align:middle line:84%
where we have
everything we need.

00:28:19.110 --> 00:28:21.260 align:middle line:84%
We have the income
and the balance sheet.

00:28:21.260 --> 00:28:24.080 align:middle line:84%
Oh yeah, so here
are these accounts.

00:28:24.080 --> 00:28:26.330 align:middle line:84%
This, I think,
was the first time

00:28:26.330 --> 00:28:29.750 align:middle line:84%
the accounts started
to come up explicitly.

00:28:29.750 --> 00:28:34.370 align:middle line:84%
We used the Thai monthly
data over 13 years,

00:28:34.370 --> 00:28:37.940 align:middle line:84%
and I featured net
income to be profits,

00:28:37.940 --> 00:28:40.280 align:middle line:90%
to be revenue minus costs.

00:28:40.280 --> 00:28:43.940 align:middle line:84%
And then we looked
at the assets to be

00:28:43.940 --> 00:28:46.490 align:middle line:84%
assets of various
kinds, typically

00:28:46.490 --> 00:28:48.830 align:middle line:90%
physical tangible assets.

00:28:48.830 --> 00:28:51.270 align:middle line:84%
So here you have the income
statement and the balance

00:28:51.270 --> 00:28:51.770 align:middle line:90%
sheet.

00:28:51.770 --> 00:28:54.510 align:middle line:84%
I just didn't call
it that at the time,

00:28:54.510 --> 00:28:56.310 align:middle line:90%
but that's what we're using.

00:28:56.310 --> 00:28:58.640 align:middle line:84%
So then we tested
the model, and found

00:28:58.640 --> 00:29:01.190 align:middle line:84%
that the betas, the
expected returns,

00:29:01.190 --> 00:29:04.230 align:middle line:84%
are indeed higher when
the betas are higher,

00:29:04.230 --> 00:29:07.190 align:middle line:90%
just like the model predicted.

00:29:07.190 --> 00:29:11.270 align:middle line:84%
And here, we are back to
idiosyncratic and aggregate

00:29:11.270 --> 00:29:13.820 align:middle line:84%
risk, which was a
theme I mentioned

00:29:13.820 --> 00:29:15.510 align:middle line:90%
in the previous lecture.

00:29:15.510 --> 00:29:22.250 align:middle line:84%
We can decompose the aggregate
variation of household j,

00:29:22.250 --> 00:29:24.530 align:middle line:84%
and explain the
unexplained part.

00:29:24.530 --> 00:29:26.960 align:middle line:84%
The explained part has to
do with the covariation

00:29:26.960 --> 00:29:28.670 align:middle line:90%
with the village average.

00:29:28.670 --> 00:29:32.630 align:middle line:84%
And the unexplained part is just
there were some idiosyncratic

00:29:32.630 --> 00:29:33.650 align:middle line:90%
risk.

00:29:33.650 --> 00:29:36.920 align:middle line:84%
And we decompose
the risk premium

00:29:36.920 --> 00:29:40.640 align:middle line:84%
as well into the
part that's coming

00:29:40.640 --> 00:29:45.650 align:middle line:84%
from the village as a whole,
through the beta j, as well as

00:29:45.650 --> 00:29:50.600 align:middle line:84%
the sigma square sigma
j on that epsilon.

00:29:50.600 --> 00:29:52.950 align:middle line:84%
And then got another
decomposition.

00:29:52.950 --> 00:29:56.450 align:middle line:84%
So it turned out that,
as a quick review,

00:29:56.450 --> 00:30:00.470 align:middle line:84%
idiosyncratic risk was
the largest contributor

00:30:00.470 --> 00:30:03.260 align:middle line:84%
to total risk, and
aggregate village level

00:30:03.260 --> 00:30:04.940 align:middle line:90%
risk was a small part.

00:30:04.940 --> 00:30:07.460 align:middle line:84%
So there were a lot of
idiosyncratic shocks

00:30:07.460 --> 00:30:09.650 align:middle line:84%
in these villages,
just like we imagined

00:30:09.650 --> 00:30:12.200 align:middle line:84%
that there were in
medieval England,

00:30:12.200 --> 00:30:17.120 align:middle line:84%
and also that we documented
there were in village India.

00:30:17.120 --> 00:30:19.100 align:middle line:84%
But when you looked
at the risk premia,

00:30:19.100 --> 00:30:23.900 align:middle line:84%
it went the other way,
namely most of the risk

00:30:23.900 --> 00:30:25.590 align:middle line:84%
has to do with the
aggregate risk.

00:30:25.590 --> 00:30:29.030 align:middle line:84%
So that's consistent
with them finding a way

00:30:29.030 --> 00:30:32.660 align:middle line:84%
to diversify their
idiosyncratic shocks.

00:30:32.660 --> 00:30:34.760 align:middle line:84%
And there was evidence
that I presented

00:30:34.760 --> 00:30:37.730 align:middle line:84%
that they're doing that
by gifts, and borrowing,

00:30:37.730 --> 00:30:38.930 align:middle line:90%
and lending.

00:30:38.930 --> 00:30:40.760 align:middle line:90%
And that's the mechanism.

00:30:40.760 --> 00:30:42.800 align:middle line:84%
We started out talking
about how we weren't

00:30:42.800 --> 00:30:44.570 align:middle line:90%
going to test for mechanisms.

00:30:44.570 --> 00:30:47.310 align:middle line:84%
Then we looked at
ex-anti-division of land.

00:30:47.310 --> 00:30:49.700 align:middle line:84%
Now we're looking
at ex-post gifts

00:30:49.700 --> 00:30:54.710 align:middle line:84%
and borrowing as a way of
getting from their, quote,

00:30:54.710 --> 00:30:59.520 align:middle line:84%
"production endowments" to
their ultimate consumptions.

00:30:59.520 --> 00:31:04.330 align:middle line:84%
And most of the shocks are
covered, not all of them.

00:31:04.330 --> 00:31:06.660 align:middle line:84%
So they're not
completely following

00:31:06.660 --> 00:31:10.620 align:middle line:84%
the full risk-sharing
program, but they definitely

00:31:10.620 --> 00:31:13.960 align:middle line:90%
diversified mostly 90% of it.

00:31:13.960 --> 00:31:16.770 align:middle line:84%
So then we got to
particular health shocks,

00:31:16.770 --> 00:31:21.450 align:middle line:84%
and specific Illnesses,
and I showed you

00:31:21.450 --> 00:31:26.070 align:middle line:84%
that again those illness shocks,
not production shocks, per se,

00:31:26.070 --> 00:31:30.130 align:middle line:84%
also covered by gifts largely,
although not entirely.

00:31:30.130 --> 00:31:32.430 align:middle line:84%
And when they were
not covered, they

00:31:32.430 --> 00:31:34.920 align:middle line:84%
spill over into
the labor network

00:31:34.920 --> 00:31:37.710 align:middle line:84%
with less hiring
of employed labor,

00:31:37.710 --> 00:31:41.430 align:middle line:84%
and also less purchasing
of intermediate goods

00:31:41.430 --> 00:31:43.270 align:middle line:90%
from other households.

00:31:43.270 --> 00:31:45.850 align:middle line:90%
So this was documenting that.

00:31:45.850 --> 00:31:50.250 align:middle line:84%
So this is about
kinship groups and risk

00:31:50.250 --> 00:31:54.030 align:middle line:84%
sharing in village
villages in Thailand.

00:31:54.030 --> 00:31:56.940 align:middle line:84%
It also was about an
illness as a shock.

00:31:56.940 --> 00:32:00.420 align:middle line:84%
It was not about COVID,
although it was about illness.

00:32:00.420 --> 00:32:03.300 align:middle line:84%
The illness was idiosyncratic
and not aggregate.

00:32:03.300 --> 00:32:06.330 align:middle line:84%
The closest we could get in
the Thai data to an aggregate

00:32:06.330 --> 00:32:10.590 align:middle line:84%
was watching those shrimp
ponds suffer catastrophe

00:32:10.590 --> 00:32:12.570 align:middle line:90%
in one of the four provinces.

00:32:12.570 --> 00:32:15.060 align:middle line:84%
And because it becomes an
aggregate shock rather than

00:32:15.060 --> 00:32:18.540 align:middle line:84%
idiosyncratic shock, it's the
gifts didn't come in as much,

00:32:18.540 --> 00:32:20.370 align:middle line:84%
and it's very
harder to diversify.

00:32:20.370 --> 00:32:22.860 align:middle line:84%
So that's a theme I
keep mentioning now

00:32:22.860 --> 00:32:24.960 align:middle line:90%
for the last 10 or 15 minutes.

00:32:24.960 --> 00:32:27.960 align:middle line:84%
Idiosyncratic stuff, in
principle, you can diversify.

00:32:27.960 --> 00:32:30.540 align:middle line:90%
Aggregate stuff you cannot.

00:32:30.540 --> 00:32:33.330 align:middle line:84%
But the other thing I want
to draw your attention to

00:32:33.330 --> 00:32:35.070 align:middle line:90%
is this network stuff.

00:32:35.070 --> 00:32:39.510 align:middle line:84%
So the issue is not just
in Thailand or India,

00:32:39.510 --> 00:32:45.030 align:middle line:84%
for that matter, but do these
networks exist in the US.

00:32:45.030 --> 00:32:47.340 align:middle line:90%
And what's going on with COVID?

00:32:47.340 --> 00:32:50.520 align:middle line:84%
So that inter-state
risk-sharing stuff

00:32:50.520 --> 00:32:54.480 align:middle line:84%
suggests that networks
are not necessarily local.

00:32:54.480 --> 00:32:56.220 align:middle line:90%
They could be global.

00:32:56.220 --> 00:32:59.160 align:middle line:84%
But your relatives or
other family members

00:32:59.160 --> 00:33:01.890 align:middle line:84%
are engaged in risk
sharing when you

00:33:01.890 --> 00:33:04.620 align:middle line:90%
experience a shock back home.

00:33:04.620 --> 00:33:08.940 align:middle line:84%
And then this project in
West Virginia, well Michael,

00:33:08.940 --> 00:33:10.440 align:middle line:84%
I hope you don't
mind mentioning it.

00:33:10.440 --> 00:33:14.070 align:middle line:84%
But Michael, thinking
about networks,

00:33:14.070 --> 00:33:16.440 align:middle line:84%
wondered about
networks in the US

00:33:16.440 --> 00:33:19.410 align:middle line:84%
and the advantage of
collecting our own data,

00:33:19.410 --> 00:33:22.800 align:middle line:84%
indeed would be to better
measure the networks

00:33:22.800 --> 00:33:25.500 align:middle line:84%
among relatives,
or friends, and so

00:33:25.500 --> 00:33:29.460 align:middle line:84%
on, in towns in rural
areas in West Virginia.

00:33:29.460 --> 00:33:32.820 align:middle line:84%
So everything that we've been
doing featuring Thailand,

00:33:32.820 --> 00:33:35.070 align:middle line:84%
because we have all
that data, could

00:33:35.070 --> 00:33:38.220 align:middle line:84%
be done in other
contexts like the US,

00:33:38.220 --> 00:33:40.470 align:middle line:90%
if we can add that data.

00:33:40.470 --> 00:33:42.390 align:middle line:84%
And we've definitely
decided to try

00:33:42.390 --> 00:33:45.180 align:middle line:84%
to measure these
networks as a suggestion

00:33:45.180 --> 00:33:47.350 align:middle line:90%
that Michael had from last time.

