as I'll review with you.

00:35:48.040 --> 00:35:51.850 align:middle line:84%
We did the wealth planner
stuff, looking at the balance

00:35:51.850 --> 00:35:53.410 align:middle line:90%
sheet and the income statement.

00:35:53.410 --> 00:35:55.810 align:middle line:84%
Then I went to the
other statement,

00:35:55.810 --> 00:35:57.640 align:middle line:90%
the statement of cash flow.

00:35:57.640 --> 00:36:00.740 align:middle line:84%
And we thought about
Bitcoin as an example,

00:36:00.740 --> 00:36:03.820 align:middle line:84%
having the balance sheet, and
the cash flow in one place.

00:36:03.820 --> 00:36:07.330 align:middle line:84%
And with Bitcoin, that motivated
a review of distributed

00:36:07.330 --> 00:36:12.280 align:middle line:84%
ledgers, and how it works with
currency, physical currency,

00:36:12.280 --> 00:36:14.080 align:middle line:90%
as opposed to the ledgers.

00:36:14.080 --> 00:36:16.660 align:middle line:84%
And then we touched
on Sweden and Kenya.

00:36:16.660 --> 00:36:18.790 align:middle line:84%
So this lecture
introduced Bitcoin.

00:36:18.790 --> 00:36:23.650 align:middle line:84%
It also introduced distributed
ledgers as financial accounts,

00:36:23.650 --> 00:36:26.320 align:middle line:90%
and also value transfer.

00:36:26.320 --> 00:36:30.490 align:middle line:84%
So we talked about this
statement of income.

00:36:30.490 --> 00:36:34.310 align:middle line:84%
By now, you may or not remember,
it doesn't really matter.

00:36:34.310 --> 00:36:37.810 align:middle line:84%
This household A appears
twice subsequently.

00:36:37.810 --> 00:36:40.480 align:middle line:84%
This was the first
time we introduced it

00:36:40.480 --> 00:36:42.640 align:middle line:84%
as an example of the
income statement,

00:36:42.640 --> 00:36:46.460 align:middle line:84%
and also household
A's balance sheet.

00:36:46.460 --> 00:36:49.180 align:middle line:84%
And then we started to talk
about the wealth planner.

00:36:49.180 --> 00:36:52.180 align:middle line:84%
So we implemented
this in Thailand,

00:36:52.180 --> 00:36:55.990 align:middle line:84%
maximize discount expected
utility over the lifetime,

00:36:55.990 --> 00:36:59.590 align:middle line:84%
even allowing for
bequests to their kids,

00:36:59.590 --> 00:37:03.250 align:middle line:84%
subject to the stocks
and flows constraint,

00:37:03.250 --> 00:37:06.130 align:middle line:84%
investing in risky
and safe assets,

00:37:06.130 --> 00:37:10.510 align:middle line:84%
and allowing for the risk
sharing which you don't usually

00:37:10.510 --> 00:37:12.970 align:middle line:90%
see in wealth planners.

00:37:12.970 --> 00:37:14.950 align:middle line:84%
But we know we needed
it for Thailand,

00:37:14.950 --> 00:37:18.310 align:middle line:84%
because you've already seen
how much risk sharing there is.

00:37:18.310 --> 00:37:20.080 align:middle line:84%
So we want to smooth
out the income

00:37:20.080 --> 00:37:23.890 align:middle line:84%
profile consistent with the
ins and outs of those gifts.

00:37:23.890 --> 00:37:27.760 align:middle line:84%
And the residual is the
household's exposure

00:37:27.760 --> 00:37:29.380 align:middle line:90%
to their own income shocks.

00:37:29.380 --> 00:37:32.260 align:middle line:84%
So we explained to
those Thai households

00:37:32.260 --> 00:37:34.390 align:middle line:90%
how the planner works.

00:37:34.390 --> 00:37:37.030 align:middle line:84%
And again, to
motivate this, think

00:37:37.030 --> 00:37:39.580 align:middle line:84%
about going to the doorstep
of a household living

00:37:39.580 --> 00:37:43.390 align:middle line:84%
in West Virginia, having
collected some of their data.

00:37:43.390 --> 00:37:46.000 align:middle line:84%
Or better yet, what
data do we want

00:37:46.000 --> 00:37:48.730 align:middle line:84%
to collect in West Virginia
consistent with running

00:37:48.730 --> 00:37:52.510 align:middle line:84%
this wealth planner, so
we can give them advice?

00:37:52.510 --> 00:37:55.820 align:middle line:84%
The setting would be different,
but the idea is the same.

00:37:55.820 --> 00:37:57.770 align:middle line:84%
So with the wealth
planner, we find out

00:37:57.770 --> 00:37:59.770 align:middle line:84%
how much they're planning
to give to their kids,

00:37:59.770 --> 00:38:00.670 align:middle line:90%
if anything.

00:38:00.670 --> 00:38:03.910 align:middle line:84%
We calibrated their
income processes

00:38:03.910 --> 00:38:06.160 align:middle line:90%
with trends and fluctuations.

00:38:06.160 --> 00:38:09.820 align:middle line:84%
We looked at their
committed consumption goals,

00:38:09.820 --> 00:38:13.420 align:middle line:84%
and we're very careful
about their initial wealth.

00:38:13.420 --> 00:38:15.790 align:middle line:84%
Again, you come into the
period with a certain amount

00:38:15.790 --> 00:38:19.240 align:middle line:84%
of wealth, and you could consume
it, or you could save it.

00:38:19.240 --> 00:38:21.370 align:middle line:84%
You can save it and
risky or safe assets.

00:38:21.370 --> 00:38:23.410 align:middle line:84%
In principle, you
could also borrow,

00:38:23.410 --> 00:38:26.570 align:middle line:84%
and then that is going to
determine wealth for next time.

00:38:26.570 --> 00:38:29.350 align:middle line:84%
So I probably didn't
emphasize it as much.

00:38:29.350 --> 00:38:31.420 align:middle line:84%
But this is where
the stocks and flows

00:38:31.420 --> 00:38:35.620 align:middle line:84%
are coming together again
early on, through this budget

00:38:35.620 --> 00:38:36.830 align:middle line:90%
constraint.

00:38:36.830 --> 00:38:41.350 align:middle line:84%
Initial wealth and
consumption is subtracted off,

00:38:41.350 --> 00:38:45.040 align:middle line:84%
and the remainder goes into
risky and safe assets, which

00:38:45.040 --> 00:38:47.410 align:middle line:90%
will determine wealth next time.

00:38:47.410 --> 00:38:49.810 align:middle line:84%
And then we looked
at actual flows

00:38:49.810 --> 00:38:53.230 align:middle line:84%
in the data, the
second household,

00:38:53.230 --> 00:38:57.310 align:middle line:84%
the recommendation of the
planner in terms of life cycle

00:38:57.310 --> 00:39:00.370 align:middle line:84%
which is saving up
enough when you're

00:39:00.370 --> 00:39:06.210 align:middle line:84%
relatively young to be able
to survive through older ages.

00:39:06.210 --> 00:39:08.350 align:middle line:84%
Some of these households
get in trouble.

00:39:08.350 --> 00:39:13.440 align:middle line:84%
So we try to help this guy,
giving advice and actually

00:39:13.440 --> 00:39:15.960 align:middle line:84%
talking about the
realism of the goals.

00:39:15.960 --> 00:39:19.260 align:middle line:84%
And I made the point that this
planner exists for the US.

00:39:19.260 --> 00:39:21.870 align:middle line:84%
Although I don't know that
it's particularly well designed

00:39:21.870 --> 00:39:24.120 align:middle line:84%
for households in
West Virginia, it

00:39:24.120 --> 00:39:28.050 align:middle line:84%
does take into account
details of the US tax code,

00:39:28.050 --> 00:39:32.310 align:middle line:84%
and Social Security, and so
on, but acting as if there's

00:39:32.310 --> 00:39:34.740 align:middle line:90%
no networks, no risk sharing.

00:39:34.740 --> 00:39:35.760 align:middle line:90%
Who knows?

00:39:35.760 --> 00:39:37.930 align:middle line:90%
We'll eventually find out.

00:39:37.930 --> 00:39:42.000 align:middle line:84%
Then I made this transition
to Bitcoin as an account.

00:39:42.000 --> 00:39:45.150 align:middle line:84%
So Bitcoin accounts have
the ownership of the coin,

00:39:45.150 --> 00:39:47.890 align:middle line:84%
and also a way to
buy something else

00:39:47.890 --> 00:39:50.670 align:middle line:84%
and transfer the coin
to a third party,

00:39:50.670 --> 00:39:55.300 align:middle line:84%
by sending the proposed
transection to be validated.

00:39:55.300 --> 00:39:59.550 align:middle line:84%
So the Bitcoin ledgers
are a combination

00:39:59.550 --> 00:40:03.160 align:middle line:84%
of the balance sheet and
the statement of cash flow.

00:40:03.160 --> 00:40:06.060 align:middle line:84%
And with the introduction
of the idea of cash flow,

00:40:06.060 --> 00:40:08.460 align:middle line:84%
I went back to the
Thai financial accounts

00:40:08.460 --> 00:40:10.365 align:middle line:84%
to look at that
for the first time.

00:40:10.365 --> 00:40:12.490 align:middle line:84%
We'd already looked at the
income and balance sheet

00:40:12.490 --> 00:40:12.990 align:middle line:90%
statement.

00:40:12.990 --> 00:40:15.480 align:middle line:84%
Now we're looking at
the cash flow statement.

00:40:15.480 --> 00:40:18.720 align:middle line:84%
Cash flow from production,
consumption, financing,

00:40:18.720 --> 00:40:20.850 align:middle line:90%
and so on.

00:40:20.850 --> 00:40:24.360 align:middle line:84%
So then the issue is,
what do the ledgers do?

00:40:24.360 --> 00:40:29.180 align:middle line:84%
Well, in Thailand, they're
largely using paper currency.

00:40:29.180 --> 00:40:31.370 align:middle line:90%
So they do not keep accounts.

00:40:31.370 --> 00:40:33.620 align:middle line:90%
And there are no common ledgers.

00:40:33.620 --> 00:40:37.760 align:middle line:84%
Bitcoin is all on an account,
and there are common ledgers.

00:40:37.760 --> 00:40:41.030 align:middle line:84%
That's why it's called a
distributed common ledger.

00:40:41.030 --> 00:40:44.780 align:middle line:84%
So we actually went
to create ledgers

00:40:44.780 --> 00:40:46.820 align:middle line:84%
that would be common
in the Thai data,

00:40:46.820 --> 00:40:49.160 align:middle line:84%
and discovered a lot
of data discrepancies

00:40:49.160 --> 00:40:52.040 align:middle line:84%
because we hadn't
collected the data that way

00:40:52.040 --> 00:40:53.040 align:middle line:90%
in the first place.

00:40:53.040 --> 00:40:55.100 align:middle line:84%
This is also a
reminder, if we're

00:40:55.100 --> 00:40:58.220 align:middle line:84%
collecting data in
West Virginia and we're

00:40:58.220 --> 00:41:01.040 align:middle line:84%
getting the identity of
the transacting partner

00:41:01.040 --> 00:41:04.040 align:middle line:84%
when we interview that
partner, those transactions

00:41:04.040 --> 00:41:05.270 align:middle line:90%
should also show up.

00:41:05.270 --> 00:41:08.030 align:middle line:84%
So ideally one would
do that in real time

00:41:08.030 --> 00:41:12.050 align:middle line:84%
almost, when memory
is fresh, or for that

00:41:12.050 --> 00:41:14.540 align:middle line:84%
matter their understanding
of a transection

00:41:14.540 --> 00:41:17.240 align:middle line:84%
with a commercial bank
which is opposed to what

00:41:17.240 --> 00:41:18.350 align:middle line:90%
commercial bank is doing.

00:41:18.350 --> 00:41:21.050 align:middle line:84%
At least you think
that, of course,

00:41:21.050 --> 00:41:22.640 align:middle line:90%
the commercial banks are honest.

00:41:22.640 --> 00:41:26.600 align:middle line:84%
Just remember Wells Fargo
that actually created accounts

00:41:26.600 --> 00:41:28.970 align:middle line:84%
for households they
didn't know about,

00:41:28.970 --> 00:41:31.910 align:middle line:84%
and then charged
them money for it.

00:41:31.910 --> 00:41:36.170 align:middle line:84%
So we then talked about
the advantage of Bitcoin

00:41:36.170 --> 00:41:40.760 align:middle line:84%
like distributed ledgers,
namely data reconciliation.

00:41:40.760 --> 00:41:44.210 align:middle line:84%
But in practice, of course,
they're using paper currency.

00:41:44.210 --> 00:41:46.550 align:middle line:84%
So with that
opportunity, we looked

00:41:46.550 --> 00:41:50.490 align:middle line:84%
at another problem
of management,

00:41:50.490 --> 00:41:55.370 align:middle line:84%
which is managing the currency,
managing the cash flow, which

00:41:55.370 --> 00:41:58.340 align:middle line:84%
we modeled and fit to the
data, as having trends

00:41:58.340 --> 00:42:00.680 align:middle line:90%
and stochastic fluctuations.

00:42:00.680 --> 00:42:03.740 align:middle line:84%
We have the evolution
of cash flow,

00:42:03.740 --> 00:42:07.610 align:middle line:84%
adjusted taking into account
the ups and downs with shocks

00:42:07.610 --> 00:42:09.770 align:middle line:84%
of revenues and
expenses, and adjusted

00:42:09.770 --> 00:42:12.350 align:middle line:90%
by withdrawals and deposits.

00:42:12.350 --> 00:42:14.900 align:middle line:84%
The two costs were
going to the bank

00:42:14.900 --> 00:42:17.570 align:middle line:84%
to make the physical
adjustment, and the opportunity

00:42:17.570 --> 00:42:20.210 align:middle line:84%
cost, foregone
interest, of holding

00:42:20.210 --> 00:42:22.250 align:middle line:90%
the currency in the house.

00:42:22.250 --> 00:42:25.685 align:middle line:84%
Which led to another
optimization problem.

00:42:25.685 --> 00:42:29.360 align:middle line:84%
Now minimizing the
expected costs,

00:42:29.360 --> 00:42:32.420 align:middle line:84%
let me just say that our
vision for West Virginia

00:42:32.420 --> 00:42:38.090 align:middle line:84%
is to combine the high frequency
cash flow with the longer term

00:42:38.090 --> 00:42:39.230 align:middle line:90%
life cycle.

00:42:39.230 --> 00:42:42.450 align:middle line:84%
Because in practice they
are intimately related.

00:42:42.450 --> 00:42:46.190 align:middle line:84%
So we'll have a synthesis
of those frameworks in mind.

00:42:46.190 --> 00:42:50.000 align:middle line:84%
And in Thailand, they didn't
manage the currency very well.

00:42:50.000 --> 00:42:52.970 align:middle line:84%
In the rural areas, they're
holding far too much of it.

00:42:52.970 --> 00:42:56.490 align:middle line:84%
And in the urban areas,
they actually did better.

00:42:56.490 --> 00:42:58.430 align:middle line:84%
Of course, one
advantage of getting

00:42:58.430 --> 00:43:01.580 align:middle line:84%
them to switch
from paper currency

00:43:01.580 --> 00:43:04.520 align:middle line:84%
into electronic entries
that is then in principle,

00:43:04.520 --> 00:43:09.740 align:middle line:84%
it's easier to manage portfolios
or to send reminders about cash

00:43:09.740 --> 00:43:15.350 align:middle line:84%
management on apps on phones,
if all the transactions

00:43:15.350 --> 00:43:16.430 align:middle line:90%
are electronic.

00:43:16.430 --> 00:43:19.550 align:middle line:84%
And I give you some
examples of Yodlee

00:43:19.550 --> 00:43:25.830 align:middle line:84%
and other apps that do this,
that collect electronic data.

00:43:25.830 --> 00:43:29.720 align:middle line:84%
So anyway, that led
finally to, well,

00:43:29.720 --> 00:43:31.670 align:middle line:84%
do you have to use
paper currency?

00:43:31.670 --> 00:43:33.320 align:middle line:90%
The answer being no.

00:43:33.320 --> 00:43:36.440 align:middle line:84%
Sweden doesn't much
anymore, although they're

00:43:36.440 --> 00:43:38.870 align:middle line:84%
worried about it in
the sense of worried

00:43:38.870 --> 00:43:42.500 align:middle line:84%
that the private sector takes
over all of the payments,

00:43:42.500 --> 00:43:46.310 align:middle line:84%
and the Riksbank isn't needed
anymore, the central bank.

00:43:46.310 --> 00:43:49.220 align:middle line:84%
And the stuff in
between, which was Kenya,

00:43:49.220 --> 00:43:54.830 align:middle line:84%
so Kenya eMoney, digital money,
is created by the cell phone

00:43:54.830 --> 00:43:57.770 align:middle line:84%
company, allowing people
to cash in and cash

00:43:57.770 --> 00:44:01.970 align:middle line:84%
out, and electronically
transfer the credits on the cell

00:44:01.970 --> 00:44:05.390 align:middle line:84%
account, which turned out
to help with guess what?

00:44:05.390 --> 00:44:06.050 align:middle line:90%
Risk sharing.

00:44:06.050 --> 00:44:10.070 align:middle line:84%
So you see a tie-in here back
to those risk-sharing lectures.

00:44:10.070 --> 00:44:12.740 align:middle line:84%
In this case, it's in
the context of Kenya,

00:44:12.740 --> 00:44:17.210 align:middle line:84%
and the fact that your
kin back in the village

00:44:17.210 --> 00:44:20.060 align:middle line:84%
have had a terrible
harvest can be

00:44:20.060 --> 00:44:23.660 align:middle line:84%
mitigated by having the
migrant worker in Nairobi

00:44:23.660 --> 00:44:24.680 align:middle line:90%
send more money.

00:44:24.680 --> 00:44:26.900 align:middle line:84%
And evidently, that
is exactly what

00:44:26.900 --> 00:44:31.580 align:middle line:84%
happens, as opposed to having
to give the Kenyan shillings,

00:44:31.580 --> 00:44:33.500 align:middle line:90%
paper currency, to a friend.

00:44:33.500 --> 00:44:35.600 align:middle line:84%
Put it in an envelope,
hope for the best,

00:44:35.600 --> 00:44:41.270 align:middle line:84%
or in a very costly way go back
home and hand over the cash.

00:44:41.270 --> 00:44:44.090 align:middle line:84%
So risk sharing on the
ledgers actually helped.

00:44:44.090 --> 00:44:46.190 align:middle line:90%
But these are private accounts.

00:44:46.190 --> 00:44:50.000 align:middle line:84%
So they don't have
what we typically

00:44:50.000 --> 00:44:52.130 align:middle line:84%
refer to as distributed
ledgers, where

00:44:52.130 --> 00:44:54.390 align:middle line:90%
there's third-party validation.

00:44:54.390 --> 00:44:57.500 align:middle line:84%
All of these transactions,
cell phone companies accounts,

00:44:57.500 --> 00:45:00.290 align:middle line:90%
are trusted to be accurate.

00:45:00.290 --> 00:45:02.450 align:middle line:84%
Households can check
them, when they

00:45:02.450 --> 00:45:05.150 align:middle line:84%
happen to see if
they get credited

00:45:05.150 --> 00:45:06.710 align:middle line:90%
the way they're supposed to.

00:45:06.710 --> 00:45:11.030 align:middle line:84%
But other than that, Safaricom
could steal the money

00:45:11.030 --> 00:45:12.290 align:middle line:90%
if they wanted to.

00:45:12.290 --> 00:45:13.820 align:middle line:90%
They don't, evidently.

00:45:13.820 --> 00:45:16.010 align:middle line:84%
They put it in the
bank, but still,

00:45:16.010 --> 00:45:18.090 align:middle line:84%
and the banks are
subject to runs.

00:45:18.090 --> 00:45:20.280 align:middle line:84%
So there's a lot
of risk remaining,

00:45:20.280 --> 00:45:25.980 align:middle line:84%
even though this digital
currency is an innovation

00:45:25.980 --> 00:45:27.150 align:middle line:90%
in the context of Kenya.

00:45:27.150 --> 00:45:29.640 align:middle line:84%
It certainly would not be
in the context of Sweden.

00:45:29.640 --> 00:45:32.380 align:middle line:84%
They have their own
interbank method.

00:45:32.380 --> 00:45:35.040 align:middle line:84%
So are there questions
about this lecture 10?

00:45:35.040 --> 00:45:38.570 align:middle line:90%


00:45:38.570 --> 00:45:40.530 align:middle line:90%
Again, it's kind of a mouthful.

00:45:40.530 --> 00:45:43.860 align:middle line:84%
This lecture does both
the financial accounts,

00:45:43.860 --> 00:45:46.910 align:middle line:84%
income statement, balance
sheet, and cash flow,

00:45:46.910 --> 00:45:51.470 align:middle line:84%
and is also looking at two
problems namely cash management

00:45:51.470 --> 00:45:55.340 align:middle line:84%
and lifecycle management,
and finally merging

00:45:55.340 --> 00:45:58.820 align:middle line:84%
into a discussion of what
distributed ledgers, Bitcoin

00:45:58.820 --> 00:46:01.410 align:middle line:84%
and distributed
ledgers, do or don't do,

00:46:01.410 --> 00:46:03.680 align:middle line:90%
and potential substitutes.

00:46:03.680 --> 00:46:08.390 align:middle line:84%
How good or how bad is currency
and Safaricom digital credits,

00:46:08.390 --> 00:46:10.820 align:middle line:90%
relative to validated systems?

00:46:10.820 --> 00:46:12.980 align:middle line:84%
Although we haven't really
talked about validation.

00:46:12.980 --> 00:46:16.530 align:middle line:84%
That happens I think
in the next lecture.

00:46:16.530 --> 00:46:19.190 align:middle line:90%
So that was lecture 10.

00:46:19.190 --> 00:46:23.900 align:middle line:84%
Lecture 11 was about contracts
and mechanism design.

00:46:23.900 --> 00:46:26.930 align:middle line:90%
And I'll just give an overview.

00:46:26.930 --> 00:46:29.940 align:middle line:84%
There were two parts
to this lecture.

00:46:29.940 --> 00:46:32.060 align:middle line:84%
The first part is
figuring out what

00:46:32.060 --> 00:46:34.550 align:middle line:84%
to do when there's
private information.

00:46:34.550 --> 00:46:37.880 align:middle line:84%
And the main conclusion
was there is a way

00:46:37.880 --> 00:46:41.570 align:middle line:84%
to write down additional
constraints, called truth

00:46:41.570 --> 00:46:43.550 align:middle line:84%
telling or incentive
constraints,

00:46:43.550 --> 00:46:47.130 align:middle line:84%
that capture the problem
of private information.

00:46:47.130 --> 00:46:50.240 align:middle line:84%
And we will be able
to append those

00:46:50.240 --> 00:46:53.600 align:middle line:84%
on top of the usual
programming problems

00:46:53.600 --> 00:46:56.875 align:middle line:84%
that maximize the lambda
weighted sums of utilities.

00:46:56.875 --> 00:46:58.250 align:middle line:84%
So we've got a
tool, and the tool

00:46:58.250 --> 00:47:00.110 align:middle line:84%
is getting better and
better, because we

00:47:00.110 --> 00:47:01.890 align:middle line:90%
can do more and more with it.

00:47:01.890 --> 00:47:03.860 align:middle line:84%
So that was one of the
main points of this.

00:47:03.860 --> 00:47:06.650 align:middle line:84%
And the other was to
think about mechanism

00:47:06.650 --> 00:47:11.300 align:middle line:84%
design, private contracts,
having to do with messages,

00:47:11.300 --> 00:47:14.210 align:middle line:84%
and then back to
the ledgers which

00:47:14.210 --> 00:47:16.940 align:middle line:84%
have to do with the
cryptography part of ledgers,

00:47:16.940 --> 00:47:20.180 align:middle line:84%
and keeping messages secret,
and whether or not they

00:47:20.180 --> 00:47:21.780 align:middle line:90%
have to be validated.

00:47:21.780 --> 00:47:24.740 align:middle line:84%
So the motivation
for the first part

00:47:24.740 --> 00:47:27.830 align:middle line:84%
was the fact that
some of these villages

00:47:27.830 --> 00:47:31.700 align:middle line:84%
lie far away from the
central monastery.

00:47:31.700 --> 00:47:33.440 align:middle line:90%
Some are very near.

00:47:33.440 --> 00:47:36.680 align:middle line:84%
Some households work
as serfs, slaves.

00:47:36.680 --> 00:47:38.910 align:middle line:90%
Others far away pay rent.

00:47:38.910 --> 00:47:43.520 align:middle line:84%
So we wanted to explain
this kind of variation

00:47:43.520 --> 00:47:46.800 align:middle line:84%
in the organizations
that we see.

00:47:46.800 --> 00:47:50.960 align:middle line:84%
So we introduced a simple
two-agent model, where only one

00:47:50.960 --> 00:47:56.570 align:middle line:84%
of the two, agent 1, had some
privately observed endowment.

00:47:56.570 --> 00:47:59.420 align:middle line:84%
Agent 2 was the villa
or the monastery.

00:47:59.420 --> 00:48:03.170 align:middle line:84%
And we wanted to know what
would be an optimal resource

00:48:03.170 --> 00:48:06.140 align:middle line:84%
allocation mechanism,
granted that agent 1 has

00:48:06.140 --> 00:48:07.470 align:middle line:90%
private information.

00:48:07.470 --> 00:48:13.130 align:middle line:84%
So we did some derivation,
had agent 1 sending messages,

00:48:13.130 --> 00:48:15.950 align:middle line:84%
looked at what would be
a maximizing message,

00:48:15.950 --> 00:48:18.860 align:middle line:84%
derived a series
of inequalities,

00:48:18.860 --> 00:48:21.920 align:middle line:84%
and then changed the
problems to sending messages

00:48:21.920 --> 00:48:25.010 align:middle line:84%
about the underlying
endowment, and ended up

00:48:25.010 --> 00:48:28.100 align:middle line:84%
with something we call the
truth telling constraint, which

00:48:28.100 --> 00:48:31.040 align:middle line:84%
captures all of the
problems associated

00:48:31.040 --> 00:48:34.170 align:middle line:84%
with private information
in this context.

00:48:34.170 --> 00:48:37.640 align:middle line:84%
So then we're able to solve for
optimal resource allocations

00:48:37.640 --> 00:48:42.290 align:middle line:84%
just by adding on these kinds
of incentive constraints,

00:48:42.290 --> 00:48:45.080 align:middle line:84%
in addition to maximizing
the lambda weighted sums

00:48:45.080 --> 00:48:46.250 align:middle line:90%
of utilities.

00:48:46.250 --> 00:48:47.960 align:middle line:90%
We did this in levels.

00:48:47.960 --> 00:48:51.140 align:middle line:84%
Then we went to lotteries
to make it more general.

00:48:51.140 --> 00:48:53.210 align:middle line:84%
We had a good discussion
at the beginning of one

00:48:53.210 --> 00:48:56.390 align:middle line:84%
of the classes of the advantages
of these lotteries, which

00:48:56.390 --> 00:49:00.440 align:middle line:84%
we had talked about in the first
one third of the class as well.

00:49:00.440 --> 00:49:04.250 align:middle line:84%
Oh, and at some point,
there was a starred article

00:49:04.250 --> 00:49:07.130 align:middle line:84%
on the reading list,
which was how to actually

00:49:07.130 --> 00:49:08.970 align:middle line:90%
code these things up.

00:49:08.970 --> 00:49:11.060 align:middle line:84%
It's more related
to the next lecture.

00:49:11.060 --> 00:49:15.540 align:middle line:84%
But anyway, trying not
to be abstract about it.

00:49:15.540 --> 00:49:17.810 align:middle line:84%
So then we went from one
period to two periods.

00:49:17.810 --> 00:49:20.150 align:middle line:84%
We solved the
two-period problem,

00:49:20.150 --> 00:49:23.030 align:middle line:84%
and had incentive
constraints, truth telling

00:49:23.030 --> 00:49:24.920 align:middle line:90%
constraints for both periods.

00:49:24.920 --> 00:49:27.890 align:middle line:84%
In this case, what
I was emphasizing

00:49:27.890 --> 00:49:30.470 align:middle line:84%
both the dynamic program
and how to work back

00:49:30.470 --> 00:49:33.500 align:middle line:84%
from the second period to the
first period sequentially,

00:49:33.500 --> 00:49:36.950 align:middle line:84%
but also the fact that
moving forward from the first

00:49:36.950 --> 00:49:40.370 align:middle line:84%
to the second, the message
is about underlying

00:49:40.370 --> 00:49:43.970 align:middle line:84%
unobserved states would
be key to implementing

00:49:43.970 --> 00:49:47.400 align:middle line:84%
the optimal information
constrained solution.

00:49:47.400 --> 00:49:50.120 align:middle line:84%
And by emphasizing
messages, I was already

00:49:50.120 --> 00:49:53.480 align:middle line:84%
anticipating contracts,
smart contracts,

00:49:53.480 --> 00:49:58.190 align:middle line:84%
written on ledgers where
messages replace transactions.

00:49:58.190 --> 00:50:01.250 align:middle line:84%
And the optimal solution
to that two-period problem

00:50:01.250 --> 00:50:04.550 align:middle line:84%
was neither full insurance
which wouldn't be feasible,

00:50:04.550 --> 00:50:08.060 align:middle line:84%
nor limited borrowing and
lending which was not optimal.

00:50:08.060 --> 00:50:10.910 align:middle line:84%
And again, in class, we
had a very good discussion

00:50:10.910 --> 00:50:14.390 align:middle line:84%
about this hybrid borrowing
and lending scheme.

00:50:14.390 --> 00:50:16.730 align:middle line:84%
We did costly
state verification.

00:50:16.730 --> 00:50:21.080 align:middle line:84%
I won't dwell on that, except
that over a range of shocks,

00:50:21.080 --> 00:50:24.410 align:middle line:84%
you don't need to be
verifying anything at all.

00:50:24.410 --> 00:50:26.690 align:middle line:84%
But it's still effective,
because there's the threat

00:50:26.690 --> 00:50:30.560 align:middle line:90%
of an audit for low claims.

00:50:30.560 --> 00:50:35.720 align:middle line:84%
And we went back and argued
that costly state verification

00:50:35.720 --> 00:50:38.810 align:middle line:84%
can help explain what we
saw in the initial part

00:50:38.810 --> 00:50:39.720 align:middle line:90%
of the lecture.

00:50:39.720 --> 00:50:43.760 align:middle line:84%
So here is where the transition
happened to distributed ledgers

00:50:43.760 --> 00:50:44.810 align:middle line:90%
again.

00:50:44.810 --> 00:50:48.080 align:middle line:84%
And there was a lot
of material here.

00:50:48.080 --> 00:50:53.030 align:middle line:84%
I kind of argued that encryption
was one third key element

00:50:53.030 --> 00:50:54.470 align:middle line:90%
of distributed ledgers.

00:50:54.470 --> 00:50:56.520 align:middle line:90%
We've seen it historically.

00:50:56.520 --> 00:50:59.930 align:middle line:84%
We see it in contemporary
applications.

00:50:59.930 --> 00:51:02.510 align:middle line:84%
It really breaks
down into encryption,

00:51:02.510 --> 00:51:04.400 align:middle line:84%
of incoming and
outgoing messages,

00:51:04.400 --> 00:51:08.390 align:middle line:84%
of hashing of data and others
so that it's uninterpretable

00:51:08.390 --> 00:51:12.380 align:middle line:84%
unless one wants to prove that
it was the original, which

00:51:12.380 --> 00:51:15.980 align:middle line:84%
is possible to do in crypto
graphic puzzles, which

00:51:15.980 --> 00:51:18.650 align:middle line:84%
are hard, but not
impossible to solve.

00:51:18.650 --> 00:51:22.710 align:middle line:84%
Bitcoin is using
various of those things,

00:51:22.710 --> 00:51:27.650 align:middle line:84%
including a way of organizing
the data through mining

00:51:27.650 --> 00:51:28.790 align:middle line:90%
as the validation.

00:51:28.790 --> 00:51:33.140 align:middle line:84%
And I emphasized that
mining was not the only way

00:51:33.140 --> 00:51:37.130 align:middle line:84%
to validate transactions on
ledgers, if you don't trust

00:51:37.130 --> 00:51:40.100 align:middle line:90%
Safaricom or some third party.

00:51:40.100 --> 00:51:43.080 align:middle line:84%
And I also emphasized
the encryption part,

00:51:43.080 --> 00:51:47.060 align:middle line:84%
which Bitcoin doesn't use,
homomorphic and that's

00:51:47.060 --> 00:51:48.260 align:middle line:90%
not quite fair.

00:51:48.260 --> 00:51:50.090 align:middle line:84%
The encryption part
for the messages

00:51:50.090 --> 00:51:52.880 align:middle line:84%
is related to
homomorphic encryption.

00:51:52.880 --> 00:51:56.550 align:middle line:84%
But Bitcoin doesn't use
multiparty computation.

00:51:56.550 --> 00:52:00.080 align:middle line:84%
So then we came back to the
essence of the lecture, which

00:52:00.080 --> 00:52:03.350 align:middle line:84%
was, what is the difference
between validation

00:52:03.350 --> 00:52:07.700 align:middle line:84%
on distributed ledgers and
incentives and mechanism

00:52:07.700 --> 00:52:11.620 align:middle line:84%
design, and the different
philosophies of economics

00:52:11.620 --> 00:52:14.030 align:middle line:90%
versus computer science?

00:52:14.030 --> 00:52:16.810 align:middle line:84%
Computer science assumes
that most nodes are

00:52:16.810 --> 00:52:22.720 align:middle line:84%
honest and reliable, and designs
algorithms on the assumption

00:52:22.720 --> 00:52:26.380 align:middle line:84%
that the honest nodes will
follow the algorithms,

00:52:26.380 --> 00:52:29.320 align:middle line:84%
and just have to have
enough total nodes

00:52:29.320 --> 00:52:32.560 align:middle line:84%
relative to the faulty
nodes in the population

00:52:32.560 --> 00:52:34.010 align:middle line:90%
for those protocols to work.

00:52:34.010 --> 00:52:37.120 align:middle line:84%
But if you take the mechanism
design point of view,

00:52:37.120 --> 00:52:40.390 align:middle line:84%
the protocols may not
be incentive compatible.

00:52:40.390 --> 00:52:44.650 align:middle line:84%
Economists assume everyone's
very selfish and maximizing.

00:52:44.650 --> 00:52:47.470 align:middle line:84%
So even the miners
in Bitcoin have

00:52:47.470 --> 00:52:51.190 align:middle line:84%
to have incentives to follow
the prescribed protocol.

00:52:51.190 --> 00:52:53.560 align:middle line:84%
And that point is
true more generally.

00:52:53.560 --> 00:52:57.580 align:middle line:84%
So that kind of led to the idea
that why not separate the two

00:52:57.580 --> 00:53:02.500 align:middle line:84%
things, write down the
contract or mechanism design

00:53:02.500 --> 00:53:08.080 align:middle line:84%
problem in code as
in a smart contract,

00:53:08.080 --> 00:53:10.120 align:middle line:84%
let the parties agree
to it and make sure

00:53:10.120 --> 00:53:13.250 align:middle line:84%
that it functions the way
they think that it does,

00:53:13.250 --> 00:53:16.690 align:middle line:84%
and then send messages
to implement it?

00:53:16.690 --> 00:53:22.420 align:middle line:84%
Those messages would be
encrypted through HE and MPC.

00:53:22.420 --> 00:53:24.010 align:middle line:90%
And that's a contribution.

00:53:24.010 --> 00:53:27.700 align:middle line:84%
The mechanism design literature
assumes we have a planner.

00:53:27.700 --> 00:53:29.440 align:middle line:90%
I hate that language.

00:53:29.440 --> 00:53:33.430 align:middle line:84%
And the planner is trusted
to implement the mechanism.

00:53:33.430 --> 00:53:36.340 align:middle line:84%
What encryption does
nowadays is to get rid

00:53:36.340 --> 00:53:39.160 align:middle line:84%
of trusted third
parties and planners.

00:53:39.160 --> 00:53:41.920 align:middle line:84%
Agents can keep
secrets from each other

00:53:41.920 --> 00:53:45.370 align:middle line:84%
and implement the
optimal contract.

00:53:45.370 --> 00:53:47.210 align:middle line:90%
The ledgers still play a role.

00:53:47.210 --> 00:53:49.600 align:middle line:84%
I mean as in
borrowing and lending,

00:53:49.600 --> 00:53:54.220 align:middle line:84%
you can sequester the collateral
and have it automatically

00:53:54.220 --> 00:53:59.700 align:middle line:84%
transferred to the lender if
the borrower were to default.

00:53:59.700 --> 00:54:02.830 align:middle line:84%
So we're not claiming that we
only need the cryptography.

00:54:02.830 --> 00:54:05.420 align:middle line:90%
We also need the ledgers.

00:54:05.420 --> 00:54:07.190 align:middle line:84%
On the other hand,
you don't need

00:54:07.190 --> 00:54:10.670 align:middle line:84%
to have all the line items of
the code in the ledger being

00:54:10.670 --> 00:54:14.120 align:middle line:84%
done, as with Ethereum,
on a distributed ledger,

00:54:14.120 --> 00:54:16.470 align:middle line:84%
because that's
really, really costly.

00:54:16.470 --> 00:54:19.100 align:middle line:84%
So again, there was a
lot in this lecture.

00:54:19.100 --> 00:54:22.760 align:middle line:90%
Questions about lecture 11?

00:54:22.760 --> 00:54:27.350 align:middle line:84%
Lecture 12 was the application
of contract theory.

00:54:27.350 --> 00:54:30.410 align:middle line:84%
And we took it to
the Thai villages,

00:54:30.410 --> 00:54:33.080 align:middle line:90%
and looked at occupation choice.

00:54:33.080 --> 00:54:34.950 align:middle line:84%
There's a couple of
things going on here.

00:54:34.950 --> 00:54:37.760 align:middle line:84%
One, we now know
how to incorporate

00:54:37.760 --> 00:54:41.960 align:middle line:84%
private information, and
incentives, and collateral

00:54:41.960 --> 00:54:45.810 align:middle line:84%
by just appending extra
constraints onto the problem.

00:54:45.810 --> 00:54:51.350 align:middle line:84%
So let me start
skipping a little bit.

00:54:51.350 --> 00:54:54.170 align:middle line:84%
Will the entrepreneur
take appropriate action?

00:54:54.170 --> 00:54:55.130 align:middle line:90%
Not necessarily.

00:54:55.130 --> 00:54:57.800 align:middle line:84%
If it's not seen, then
you have to induce it.

00:54:57.800 --> 00:55:00.710 align:middle line:84%
Will the entrepreneur
pay back the loan?

00:55:00.710 --> 00:55:02.990 align:middle line:84%
If not, you have to
have collateral, which

00:55:02.990 --> 00:55:06.860 align:middle line:90%
is another kind of constraint.

00:55:06.860 --> 00:55:10.910 align:middle line:84%
So here we have the household's
utility in consumption,

00:55:10.910 --> 00:55:14.000 align:middle line:84%
and a disutility of
effort, and potentially

00:55:14.000 --> 00:55:16.460 align:middle line:84%
risk neutral,
potentially risk averse.

00:55:16.460 --> 00:55:21.060 align:middle line:84%
And households vary by
talent, wealth, and schooling.

00:55:21.060 --> 00:55:24.380 align:middle line:84%
And we have they're running
a firm with stochastic output

00:55:24.380 --> 00:55:27.320 align:middle line:84%
as a function of
effort and capital.

00:55:27.320 --> 00:55:29.510 align:middle line:90%
And they can borrow.

00:55:29.510 --> 00:55:32.540 align:middle line:84%
This is the slide I was
kind of racing to get to.

00:55:32.540 --> 00:55:36.470 align:middle line:84%
So here is the
problem, which we posed

00:55:36.470 --> 00:55:40.070 align:middle line:84%
as maximizing the
utility of the borrower

00:55:40.070 --> 00:55:45.530 align:middle line:84%
or entrepreneur, subject to
the bank making zero profits.

00:55:45.530 --> 00:55:49.670 align:middle line:84%
So it's worth emphasizing
that in the previous lecture,

00:55:49.670 --> 00:55:53.210 align:middle line:84%
as we've been maximizing lambda
weighted sums of utilities

00:55:53.210 --> 00:55:55.880 align:middle line:84%
subject to resource
constraints, and incentive

00:55:55.880 --> 00:55:57.320 align:middle line:90%
constraints, and so on.

00:55:57.320 --> 00:55:59.780 align:middle line:84%
Well, here we made a
shift from maximizing

00:55:59.780 --> 00:56:02.870 align:middle line:84%
the utility of one party,
subject to a fixed utility

00:56:02.870 --> 00:56:03.500 align:middle line:90%
of the other.

00:56:03.500 --> 00:56:05.900 align:middle line:84%
Or here, the utility
of the entrepreneur

00:56:05.900 --> 00:56:09.920 align:middle line:84%
subject to a fixed and zero
profit level of the bank.

00:56:09.920 --> 00:56:12.050 align:middle line:84%
One could have solved
this problem the other way

00:56:12.050 --> 00:56:15.410 align:middle line:84%
around, to maximize the
profits of the bank subject

00:56:15.410 --> 00:56:20.040 align:middle line:84%
to a fixed reservation utility
on the part of the borrower.

00:56:20.040 --> 00:56:21.860 align:middle line:90%
You should get the same answers.

00:56:21.860 --> 00:56:24.210 align:middle line:84%
Of course, there are
many, many solutions--

00:56:24.210 --> 00:56:26.570 align:middle line:84%
if you allow profits
to be positive,

00:56:26.570 --> 00:56:31.190 align:middle line:84%
if you allow some of the surplus
to go to the bank, et cetera.

00:56:31.190 --> 00:56:34.220 align:middle line:84%
In fact, the borrower could
be pushed down to the point

00:56:34.220 --> 00:56:37.910 align:middle line:84%
that they're almost
indifferent to participating

00:56:37.910 --> 00:56:41.520 align:middle line:84%
if the banks are getting
the bulk of the surplus.

00:56:41.520 --> 00:56:45.110 align:middle line:84%
But what I want to emphasize is
it's all the same in the end.

00:56:45.110 --> 00:56:47.600 align:middle line:84%
Maximizing lambda
weighted sum of utilities

00:56:47.600 --> 00:56:50.630 align:middle line:84%
is the same as maximizing
the utility of one type,

00:56:50.630 --> 00:56:54.890 align:middle line:84%
subject to fixed utility of the
other, and then varying those.

00:56:54.890 --> 00:56:59.720 align:middle line:84%
So the rest of it was just
implementing the solution,

00:56:59.720 --> 00:57:04.430 align:middle line:84%
limited liability, moral
hazard, with separate equations.

00:57:04.430 --> 00:57:06.920 align:middle line:84%
And then we got to
this diagram where

00:57:06.920 --> 00:57:10.670 align:middle line:84%
I said, if there were no
constraints at all, that

00:57:10.670 --> 00:57:13.250 align:middle line:84%
would be like the full
information, full commitment

00:57:13.250 --> 00:57:18.260 align:middle line:84%
solution, hit the bull's eye, it
could be entirely moral hazard

00:57:18.260 --> 00:57:19.610 align:middle line:90%
and not limited liability.

00:57:19.610 --> 00:57:23.630 align:middle line:84%
It could be entirely limited
liability and not moral hazard.

00:57:23.630 --> 00:57:26.630 align:middle line:84%
Although in this case, if
you had both constraints,

00:57:26.630 --> 00:57:29.960 align:middle line:84%
you have two equations and
two unknowns, the capital

00:57:29.960 --> 00:57:31.470 align:middle line:90%
and the effort level.

00:57:31.470 --> 00:57:33.890 align:middle line:84%
So when those two
constraints are satisfied,

00:57:33.890 --> 00:57:36.230 align:middle line:84%
if they're both in
the program, you

00:57:36.230 --> 00:57:39.140 align:middle line:84%
get a solution that has
nothing to do with utility

00:57:39.140 --> 00:57:42.350 align:middle line:84%
maximization, because there's
only one point in the input

00:57:42.350 --> 00:57:46.150 align:middle line:84%
space where both
constraints are satisfied.

00:57:46.150 --> 00:57:48.865 align:middle line:84%
But in general, if you
have only one or the other,

00:57:48.865 --> 00:57:54.190 align:middle line:84%
you have both max utility and
then subject to constraints.

00:57:54.190 --> 00:57:57.460 align:middle line:84%
The rest of this lecture
was about implementation,

00:57:57.460 --> 00:58:00.730 align:middle line:84%
namely solving linear
programming problems

00:58:00.730 --> 00:58:04.840 align:middle line:84%
and trying to pick
parameters in such a way that

00:58:04.840 --> 00:58:08.620 align:middle line:84%
maximize the probability
that the model is true,

00:58:08.620 --> 00:58:11.140 align:middle line:90%
given what we see in the data.

00:58:11.140 --> 00:58:15.010 align:middle line:84%
Maximize the probability that
the data we see in reality

00:58:15.010 --> 00:58:18.600 align:middle line:84%
could have come from
the model by choosing

00:58:18.600 --> 00:58:19.860 align:middle line:90%
the parameters of the model.

00:58:19.860 --> 00:58:22.740 align:middle line:90%


00:58:22.740 --> 00:58:24.600 align:middle line:90%
That was the application.

00:58:24.600 --> 00:58:27.390 align:middle line:84%
And then we had the findings
that the constraints

00:58:27.390 --> 00:58:29.190 align:middle line:90%
varied by region.

00:58:29.190 --> 00:58:30.855 align:middle line:84%
Are the questions
about this lecture?

