close to the end here.

00:58:53.420 --> 00:58:56.400 align:middle line:84%
This lecture did two
important things.

00:58:56.400 --> 00:58:59.510 align:middle line:84%
One, the theory
which was to define

00:58:59.510 --> 00:59:02.120 align:middle line:84%
the notion of
Walrasian equilibrium

00:59:02.120 --> 00:59:03.800 align:middle line:90%
within and without transfers.

00:59:03.800 --> 00:59:05.720 align:middle line:90%
And the second was to apply it.

00:59:05.720 --> 00:59:08.750 align:middle line:84%
So we get general
equilibrium solution

00:59:08.750 --> 00:59:12.470 align:middle line:84%
in a small open economy
with production.

00:59:12.470 --> 00:59:14.600 align:middle line:84%
All of this slide
had to do with,

00:59:14.600 --> 00:59:16.430 align:middle line:90%
remember what an economy means.

00:59:16.430 --> 00:59:20.810 align:middle line:84%
This is partly review of the
first one third of the class--

00:59:20.810 --> 00:59:23.210 align:middle line:84%
numbers of households,
numbers of firms,

00:59:23.210 --> 00:59:28.370 align:middle line:84%
what consumers do, what firms
do, aggregate resources.

00:59:28.370 --> 00:59:30.303 align:middle line:90%
We went over private ownership.

00:59:30.303 --> 00:59:31.970 align:middle line:84%
And again, we had a
very good discussion

00:59:31.970 --> 00:59:34.160 align:middle line:84%
at the beginning of
the following class

00:59:34.160 --> 00:59:37.730 align:middle line:84%
to review this slide in terms
of individual endowments

00:59:37.730 --> 00:59:39.590 align:middle line:90%
and ownership shares.

00:59:39.590 --> 00:59:42.230 align:middle line:84%
And the key definition
of Walrasian

00:59:42.230 --> 00:59:46.970 align:middle line:84%
equilibrium with
three items in it--

00:59:46.970 --> 00:59:49.880 align:middle line:84%
maximizing profits
for firms, maximizing

00:59:49.880 --> 00:59:54.620 align:middle line:84%
utility for households, and the
feasibility of the allocations

00:59:54.620 --> 00:59:57.710 align:middle line:84%
that result from those
two optimization problems.

00:59:57.710 --> 01:00:01.070 align:middle line:84%
The key being that prices
are the things that

01:00:01.070 --> 01:00:03.350 align:middle line:90%
allow the reconciliation.

01:00:03.350 --> 01:00:05.060 align:middle line:90%
You can do partial equilibrium.

01:00:05.060 --> 01:00:05.870 align:middle line:90%
We did.

01:00:05.870 --> 01:00:09.230 align:middle line:84%
You can solve for profit
maximization taking prices

01:00:09.230 --> 01:00:10.100 align:middle line:90%
as given.

01:00:10.100 --> 01:00:12.260 align:middle line:84%
You can solve for
utility maximization,

01:00:12.260 --> 01:00:13.940 align:middle line:90%
taking prices as given.

01:00:13.940 --> 01:00:16.490 align:middle line:84%
Here in general
equilibrium, we are only

01:00:16.490 --> 01:00:19.460 align:middle line:84%
allowing certain prices
where those decentralized

01:00:19.460 --> 01:00:22.070 align:middle line:84%
optimization problems are
consistent with each other

01:00:22.070 --> 01:00:26.840 align:middle line:84%
in the sense that supply
is equal to demand.

01:00:26.840 --> 01:00:28.790 align:middle line:84%
Oh, and then this
Edgeworth box, which

01:00:28.790 --> 01:00:33.320 align:middle line:84%
is like economists' favorite
environment, a sad statement,

01:00:33.320 --> 01:00:36.350 align:middle line:84%
putting the two types of
households on the axis

01:00:36.350 --> 01:00:39.560 align:middle line:84%
and talking about what a
competitive equilibrium would

01:00:39.560 --> 01:00:40.500 align:middle line:90%
look like.

01:00:40.500 --> 01:00:44.210 align:middle line:84%
And the price equilibrium
with transfers and the welfare

01:00:44.210 --> 01:00:46.820 align:middle line:84%
theorems, which so far
I have only stated,

01:00:46.820 --> 01:00:49.130 align:middle line:84%
although the last one
third of the class

01:00:49.130 --> 01:00:52.790 align:middle line:84%
next week will be focusing
in part on these welfare

01:00:52.790 --> 01:00:54.480 align:middle line:90%
theorems starting next week.

01:00:54.480 --> 01:00:57.620 align:middle line:84%
So then we did production
in the small open economy.

01:00:57.620 --> 01:01:00.750 align:middle line:84%
And we again went through this
algorithm pretty carefully.

01:01:00.750 --> 01:01:03.560 align:middle line:84%
So I don't think I want
to say too much about it,

01:01:03.560 --> 01:01:04.400 align:middle line:90%
too, too much.

01:01:04.400 --> 01:01:08.150 align:middle line:84%
But we simplify the
problem down into firms

01:01:08.150 --> 01:01:12.080 align:middle line:84%
hiring inputs and trying to
find the factor prices that

01:01:12.080 --> 01:01:16.460 align:middle line:84%
clear the input markets, taking
out external prices of goods

01:01:16.460 --> 01:01:18.030 align:middle line:90%
as given.

01:01:18.030 --> 01:01:20.330 align:middle line:84%
So we had the firms
maximization problem.

01:01:20.330 --> 01:01:23.210 align:middle line:84%
We wrote down that the
sum of the input demands

01:01:23.210 --> 01:01:26.900 align:middle line:84%
equal the endowments,
and reminded ourselves

01:01:26.900 --> 01:01:27.920 align:middle line:90%
of Shepard's lemma.

01:01:27.920 --> 01:01:30.830 align:middle line:84%
So we had a different
statement of the input demands,

01:01:30.830 --> 01:01:35.360 align:middle line:84%
which we could then solve,
especially in the 2 by 2 model.

01:01:35.360 --> 01:01:39.350 align:middle line:84%
Input demands are entirely a
function of input price ratios.

01:01:39.350 --> 01:01:43.250 align:middle line:84%
And with constant returns
to scale, it's even easier.

01:01:43.250 --> 01:01:45.560 align:middle line:84%
We can talk about
cost minimization

01:01:45.560 --> 01:01:47.630 align:middle line:84%
to achieve a unit
of output, and then

01:01:47.630 --> 01:01:51.580 align:middle line:84%
to scale up and down when we
get to determining output.

01:01:51.580 --> 01:01:54.410 align:middle line:84%
We talked about the
intensity of goods,

01:01:54.410 --> 01:01:56.630 align:middle line:84%
the factor intensity
of the different goods

01:01:56.630 --> 01:01:58.040 align:middle line:90%
with a definition.

01:01:58.040 --> 01:02:01.850 align:middle line:84%
Here was the cost curves
and their properties.

01:02:01.850 --> 01:02:04.460 align:middle line:84%
Concave, we solve for
the equilibrium factor

01:02:04.460 --> 01:02:08.690 align:middle line:84%
prices, where both firms
face common prices.

01:02:08.690 --> 01:02:11.420 align:middle line:84%
Hence, there's only
one point where

01:02:11.420 --> 01:02:13.250 align:middle line:90%
that's true on this diagram.

01:02:13.250 --> 01:02:16.070 align:middle line:84%
And then we went from
that to production.

01:02:16.070 --> 01:02:18.350 align:middle line:84%
From production, we were
able to solve for the input

01:02:18.350 --> 01:02:20.120 align:middle line:90%
quantities and the outputs.

01:02:20.120 --> 01:02:24.080 align:middle line:84%
And then we got the
external goods prices

01:02:24.080 --> 01:02:28.310 align:middle line:84%
by considering the
free trade equilibrium

01:02:28.310 --> 01:02:33.200 align:middle line:84%
with two countries determining a
price ratio moving from Autarky

01:02:33.200 --> 01:02:36.170 align:middle line:90%
to international trade.

01:02:36.170 --> 01:02:38.150 align:middle line:90%
So there were three theorems.

01:02:38.150 --> 01:02:40.740 align:middle line:84%
We had this
Heckscher-Ohlin theorem,

01:02:40.740 --> 01:02:43.040 align:middle line:84%
which someone mentioned
at the beginning of class

01:02:43.040 --> 01:02:46.040 align:middle line:84%
today, that the
returns to factors

01:02:46.040 --> 01:02:49.070 align:middle line:84%
depend on whether the
country is abundant in one

01:02:49.070 --> 01:02:51.140 align:middle line:90%
factor versus another one.

01:02:51.140 --> 01:02:52.940 align:middle line:84%
The Stopler-Samuelson,
having to do

01:02:52.940 --> 01:02:55.790 align:middle line:84%
with how factor
prices are moving when

01:02:55.790 --> 01:03:00.400 align:middle line:90%
we vary the price of outputs.

01:03:00.400 --> 01:03:03.430 align:middle line:90%
And that's all.

01:03:03.430 --> 01:03:04.360 align:middle line:90%
OK.

